<FIRST>r a AM-EthicsChief     02-05 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethics Chief,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Bush Ethics Counsel Changes Story</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's ethics adviser, C. Boyden Gray,
changed his account Saturday of when he learned about a White House
policy on business interests like the large family-owned
communications company he heads, a newspaper reported.
   The New York Times reported in Sunday editions that Gray had said
in two interviews last week that he just learned on Thursday about
the policy, which limits outside business income for White House
employees. But on Saturday Gray said he had learned about the policy
in November from his deputy, John Schmitz.
   The Washington Post reported Saturday that Gray, the White House
counsel, plans to continue as chairman of his family company, Summit
Communications Inc., but will give up the fee he collected during
his eight previous years as vice presidential counsel.
   The Times quoted Gray as saying he had stopped taking fees
effective at the end of last year, and that he would have done so
earlier if he had known about the policy.
   Gray said he learned several weeks ago about a related White
House prohibition from serving on corporate boards, the Times said.
He said that policy was under review, and he would remain on the
board of his family company, according to the Times.
   Gray told the Times he complied with ethics rules by
disqualifying himself from discussing communications issues in the
government. Summit, based in Atlanta, owns 16 radio stations and
cable television outlets, the Times said.
   Gray reported his financial interests in a disclosure statement
six months past a May 15 deadline, a ``nonwillful violation of the
law,'' ethics office director Frank Nebeker told The Times.
   Gray said he had left the filing to others, the Times reported.
Schmitz blamed demands from the presidential campaign and the
55-page length of the report, the newspaper said.
   Asked about a campaign pledge by Bush in July that none of his
aides would accept outside earned income, Gray said he was unaware
of it because he was not involved in the campaign, the Times said.
The Reagan White House had a similar policy, although Gray, as a
vice presidential aide, was not technically covered by it.
</TEXT>
