<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Abortion     02-05 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Abortion,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Calls For End To Abortion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II called Sunday for a ``new
culture of solidarity'' that would protect the sick and elderly and
outlaw abortion.
   In his noon ``Angelus'' address from his window overlooking St.
Peter's Square, the pope noted that Italy's Roman Catholic Church on
Sunday was observing the ``Day of Life.''
   Cardinal Ugo Poletti, head of the Italian bishops' conference,
led a march of 3,000 people from Rome's Sant' Andrea delle Valle
Church to St. Peter's. The group carried signs with slogans such as
``Yes to Life.''
   John Paul said he hoped the initiative would increase ``the
common awareness and responsibility in one of the most dramatic
problems of our time.''
   ``The future of man is threatened, in some countries, by the
decline of births, by the aging of the population, by the widespread
recourse to abortion, by the thousands of forms of egoism,'' the
pope told the crowd of 15,000 people gathered in the square.
   ``A new culture of solidarity is needed,'' he added. ``The life
of each person, including the one waiting to be born, the one sick
or weak, the one in decline, is an absolute and intangible gift. It
is a gift of all and for all.''
</TEXT>
