<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Hess     02-05 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Hess,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Photos of Hess' Body Suggest Murder, Paper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Photographs of the body of Rudolf Hess suggest
Adolf Hitler's 93-year-old deputy may have been murdered at Spandau
Prison in West Berlin in 1987, the Sunday Observer newspaper
reported.
   The liberal weekly said it studied the pictures, which were
brought to London by Hess' son, Wolf Rudiger Hess. Hess met Friday
with Scotland Yard detectives investigating suggestions his father
did not commit suicide, said the paper.
   The photographs were part of a post-mortem report by Wolfgang
Spann of Munich, who suggested the Nazi leader died as a result of
``deliberate strangulation rather than hanging,'' the paper said.
The first post-mortem, by James Cameron of London University, said
Hess' death was a suicide by hanging.
   Dr. Hugh Thomas, a former British army doctor who examined the
Spandau prisoner in 1973, was quoted as telling the Observer the
photographs from Spann's examination show Hess was murdered.
   ``If a person hangs to death, you would expect that the line of
the cord would run diagonally across the back of his neck. But the
photographs of Hess show a mark straight across. The line also
continues around the front of the neck, suggesting he was killed by
strangulation rather than hanging,'' Thomas was quoted as saying.
   In two books, Thomas has contended Hess was murdered in 1941
while flying to Scotland on a peace mission and an impersonator in a
second plane was substituted by plotters among Hitler's deputies.
   Thomas claims the imposter spent 46 years in Hess' place at
Spandau and alleges he was murdered in 1987 to stop the leak of
details of a World War II plot by powerful Britons to overthrow
Prime Minister Winston Churchill.
   Wolf Rudiger Hess maintains the Spandau prisoner was his father
and that he probably was murdered on Aug. 17, 1987, because of
Allied fears he might disclose secrets about his flight to Scotland
in 1941.
   In a statement Saturday, Scotland Yard would not disclose who it
has interviewed for its investigation into Hess' death, which is
being conducted at the request of the director of public
prosecutions.
   At the Nuremberg war crimes trials, Hess was sentenced to life
imprisonment with no possibility of parole for ``preparing and
waging an aggressive war.''
</TEXT>
