<FIRST>r i AM-India-Punjab     02-05 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Punjab,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh Politician and Associate Killed in Punjab</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Holy Fair, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A politician opposed to the Sikh
separatist movement was shot and killed along with an associate
Sunday after making a speech calling for an end to violence in
Punjab state, police said.
   Rajender Kaur, 56, president of the women's wing of a Sikh
political party, and her colleague were attacked by suspected Sikh
militants as they left a Sikh school that was celebrating its golden
jubilee, police said.
   Both died instantly, according to R.S. Gill, the police chief in
the town of Bhatinda, 120 miles southwest of Chandigarh. He said the
assailants fired as Mrs. Kaur was getting into her car outside
Khalsa School in Bhatinda.
   The attackers fled on foot, Gill said in a telephone interview.
   Mrs. Kaur was the president of the Istri Akali Dal, the women's
wing of the Sikh Akali Dal Party, and a former member of Parliament.
She was opposed to the Sikh militant movement for an independent
homeland in Punjab and spoke against increasing violence at the
school function, Gill said.
   Her associate was identified as Baldev Singh.
   Sikh militants have been blamed for at least 200 killings in the
state this year. Last year, at least 2,400 people were killed in the
state.
   The United News of India news agency said at least six people
were killed in Punjab on Saturday. The militants usually target
members of the majority Hindu community and moderate Sikhs who
oppose their separatist campaign.
   Sikhs form 2 percent of India's 880 million people but are in a
majority in northern Punjab.
   The militants claim Sikhs are discriminated against by the
majority Hindu community, which makes up 80 percent of the country's
population.
</TEXT>
