<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Dynasty'' star Joan Collins is
selling her Beverly Hills mansion, which includes a
6,000-square-foot main house and a 2,000-square-foot guest house.
   The home was built in 1963 for Laurence Harvey, the late British
actor, and was later owned by comedian Totie Fields, the Los Angeles
Times reported Sunday.
   After Miss Collins purchased the property for about $1.9 million
in 1986, she had the place extensively renovated, and is now asking
$6 million for the mansion.
   The mansion is not the two-story Los Angeles hillside home
featured during Miss Collins' sensational divorce last year from
former Swedish rock star Peter Holm. That one was sold to filmmaker
Freddie Fields for $675,000 during the divorce proceedings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kerry Kennedy, executive director of
the Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Center for Human Rights, said private
citizens have an obligation to work for justice.
   ``Everybody can do something, whether it's holding conferences
like this or joining organizations,'' the 29-year-old daughter of
the slain political leader told a human rights conference Saturday
night. She spoke along with Costa Rican president Oscar Arias,
winner of the Nobel Peace Prize.
   Kennedy said she thought the human rights situation in Latin
America was improving, but that ``many challenges still lie ahead.''
   ``For instance, we've had the plebiscite in Chile, but (Augusto)
Pinochet is still in power,'' she said.
   Ethel Kennedy, Kerry's mother, said she agreed with her
daughter's work.
   ``My husband was very concerned that the elite were much more
interested in their own lives and not in seeing how others get by,''
she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cowboy stars Roy Rogers, Gene Autry,
Pedro Gonzales and Pat Buttram, dressed in tuxedos, rode to Rex
Allen's rescue, helping to raise $100,000 toward the establishment
of a museum in Allen's home town.
   Allen, the singing star of many 1950s Western movies, is working
to raise $250,000 to open a western museum and movie house in the
tiny southeastern Arizona town of Willcox.
   His fellow Western stars attended a fund-raiser dinner and
celebrity roast in his honor Saturday night.
   The movie house will show new films as well as old cowboy serials
and Rex Allen movies. Willcox has had no theater since 1980.
   Rogers said the serials he and the others made were perhaps the
last family westerns that offered children true heroes.
   ``We made them for the family in those days,'' Rogers said,
adding that contemporary films don't do kids any good. ``I wouldn't
even let Trigger to go to them.''
   Allen signed on with Republic Pictures in 1949. His first film,
``Arizona Cowboy,'' was released in 1950. He made 25 westerns for
Republic and played the lead in the 1950 television show ``Frontier
Doctor.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
went home Sunday from the Government Hospital, 12 days after
undergoing a heart bypass operation.
   Mahathir, 63, Malaysia's prime minister since July 1981,
underwent quintuple-bypass surgery Jan. 24.
   Hospital Director Celestine Fonseka told reporters Mahathir was
in very good health and was a model patient. In a statement,
Mahathir thanked all those who had sent messages and prayed for his
recovery.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LEVEL CROSS, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wheels have come off auto racing
star Richard Petty's upcoming debut on ``60 Minutes,'' and it was
Diane Sawyer's switch of newtorks that sent the NASCAR king into the
pits.
   A ``60 Minutes'' segment by Sawyer on Petty, scheduled to be
aired Feb. 12, apparently has been scrapped, according to Petty.
   Petty, NASCAR's all-time winner with 200 victories in 30 years,
said that he was informed Friday morning by an executive for the CBS
show that the segment had been pulled in the wake of Sawyer's
signing with ABC.
   ``As far as I know it's off right now,'' Petty said. ``Since
she's gone over to ABC, they said they don't want to show anything
with her involved.''
   ABC News last week announced it had signed Sawyer to be co-anchor
with Sam Donaldson on a new prime-time program scheduled to go on
the air later this year.
