<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0667 02-05 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Survives Assassination Attempt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs with victims shot by bodyguards; background
on previous assassination attempt; Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``The attack...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former prime minister escaped with
minor bruises Sunday when three bombs exploded at a campaign rally
and security guards responded by firing randomly. Nearly 40 people
were reported injured.
   Sirimavo Bandaranaike, who has become a top opposition leader
since leaving office, said the attempt on her life failed when a
bodyguard kicked away a grenade that was thrown at her before it
could explode. She survived a similar assassination attempt in
December while campaigning for president.
   Five thousand people were attending the outdoor rally when
unidentified assailants hurled the explosives just as Mrs.
Bandaranaike stood up to make a speech kicking off her party's
campaign for the Feb. 15 general election.
   A military official in Colombo, who cannot be identified under
briefing rules, said at least 38 people were injured, 14 seriously,
in the attack in Hingurakgoda, a remote town 100 miles northeast of
Colombo.
   Many were shot by Mrs. Bandaranaike's security guards, who shot
randomly after the bombs exploded. ``The bodyguards panicked and
opened up with rifles, pistols and shotguns, injuring a lot of
people,'' he said.
   Authorities said they were unsure who was behind the attack. At
least 10 candidates, including six from Mrs. Bandaranaike's party,
have been killed in the past month by suspected Sinhalese militants.
   The attack came one day after at least 13 people were killed in
Sri Lanka in violence related to the election.
   Mrs. Bandaranaike, 72, sustained minor bruises in a stampede that
followed the explosions, a member of her opposition Sri Lanka
Freedom Party said.
   Mrs. Bandaranaike was elected the world's first woman prime
minister in 1960. She ruled until 1965 and then again from 1970-77.
   Her husband, S.W.R.D. Bandaranaike, was prime minister when he
was assassinated by a Buddhist monk in 1959.
   She is now president of the Sri Lanka Freedom Party, the nation's
main opposition group. She was the runner-up in the presidential
election Dec. 19, losing to Ranasinghe Premadasa of the United
National Party.
   Her party has promised to reduce ethnic conflict between minority
Tamils and the majority Sinhalese, to send back Indian soldiers
enforcing a peace accord and to avoid the socialist policies she
once promoted as prime minister.
   The election, for 225 seats in Parliament, will select the next
prime minister, a post less powerful than that of president.
   Mrs. Bandaranaike refused Sunday to say who might have staged the
attack. ``We are not going to say anything at the moment,'' she told
reporters in the nearby town of Anuradhapura. ``We've got our own
investigations going.''
   Both Sinhalese militants and Tamil rebels oppose the holding of
general elections, but for different reasons.
   The Sinhalese militants, who also oppose the peace plan, have
vowed to disrupt the voting as part of their anti-government
campaign launched in 1987.
   Sinhalese extremists say the July 29, 1987 accord, designed to
end the Tamil separatist struggle, gives the Tamils too many
concessions.
   Most Tamil rebel groups approved the accord, but the largest
militia, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, reneged on the plan
and has since targeted moderate Tamils, whom they regard as traitors.
   Sinhalese form 75 percent of the country's 16 million people and
control the government and military. Tamils, who make up 18 percent
of the population, claim they are discriminated against by the
Sinhalese.
   At least 8,500 people have been killed in the Tamil separatist
war since it was launched in 1983. The Sinhalese extremists have
been blamed for another 1,000 killings since July 1987.
</TEXT>
