<FIRST>r i AM-Hussein     02-05 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hussein,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jordanian Leader Expected to Visit Washington Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein of Jordan will visit the United States
soon to discuss the Palestinian problem with President Bush, Prime
Minister Zaid Rifai was quoted as saying Sunday.
   In an interview with the Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Watan, Rifai gave
no date for the visit but said the talks will cover latest
developments in the Middle East, the Palestinian problem and the
Arab-Israeli conflict.
   There have been reports Bush would invite leading Middle East
leaders for consultations on a settlement of the 40-year
Arab-Israeli problem.
   Asked if he thought the United States would offer a new Middle
East peace initiative, Rifai said, ``We're fed up with initiatives
... the basis for a settlement and the solutions are there, and
agreed upon internationally, with the exception of the Israeli
stance.
   ``And regrettably they (Israel) are supported by the American
stance,'' he added.
   Rifai reiterated rejection of an Israeli proposal that a
settlement be negotiated at an international conference under the
aegis of only the two superpowers, the United States and the Soviet
Union.
   Arabs want an international conference under the umbrella of the
United Nations with participation of all five permanent members of
the U.N. Security Council _ the United States, Soviet Union,
Britain, France and China. They also want the Palestine Liberation
Organization represened at the talks, a suggestion rejected by
Israel.
   ``We do not want the Arab -Israeli conflict to be polarized into
a conflict between the two superpowers,'' Rifai said.
   King Hussein was in Iraq on Sunday for talks with President
Saddam Hussein that will include plans for an economic grouping with
Egypt and North Yemen, diplomatic sources said.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Rifai
accompanied Hussein.
   Before leaving for Baghdad, Hussein met briefly with Osama
El-Baz, an adviser to Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, who handed
the king a message from the Egyptian leader, according to official
sources.
   They did not say what was discussed.
   In Cairo, the Middle East New Agency said the letter from Mubarak
dealt with ``the latest developments of the situation in the Middle
East and new developments in the Arab world, and comes in the
framework of continued consultations between the two Arab leaders.''
</TEXT>
