<FIRST>u i AM-HolyFair 1stLd-Writethru a0647 02-05 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holy Fair, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>Countdown Starts For Sacred Hindu Bathing Festival</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with number of devotees. Pickup
4th pvs, ``The holy ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALLAHABAD, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of Hindus invoking their ancient
faith's countless gods and goddesses converged Sunday at the
confluence of three rivers whose waters are thought to hold the
power to wash away sins and end the cycle of birth and rebirth.
   ``At least 10 million people have already come. It's already a
sea of humanity,'' said Ravindra Gupta, pointing at the flow of
worshipers arriving in this central city for the Kumbh Mela, listed
in the Guinness Book of World Records as the world's biggest
religious gathering.
   ``People have already started taking their holy baths. They do
not want to take a chance tomorrow (Monday),'' said Gupta,
Allahabad's chief administrator.
   He said he expects 15 million people at the river banks Monday.
   The holy fair is held every 12 years by the lunar calendar at the
time of a rare planetary convergence: Jupiter in Taurus, the sun and
moon in Capricorn, and a complicated Hindu astronomical calculation
of other planets and stars.
   The Kumbh Mela began Jan. 14 and lasts seven weeks, but Monday is
considered the most auspicious time for bathing in the sacred rivers
_ the Ganges, the Yamuna and the Saraswati _ because it is the day
of the new moon.
   This year, police on horseback, in jeeps, at observation posts
and on foot are keeping close vigils for fear Sikh extremists might
launch attacks at the fair.
   ``We are ready for everything,'' said Trinath Mishra, deputy
inspector general of police in Uttar Pradesh state.
   ``This fair is a sitting duck for terrorists, but we are no
goose,'' Mishra said. ``We can counter any eventualities.''
   About 12,000 policemen and 5,000 militiamen have been deployed
around the 3,000-acre fair site. There are 25 police watchtowers
equipped with television monitors, 25 police posts, 10 river police
stations and 22 fire stations.
   Soldiers at a nearby army base are on alert.
   Allahabad is more than 425 miles from Punjab state, where radical
Sikhs have been waging a separatist war against India's Hindu
majority.
   But Sikh gunmen and bombers, who have killed about 200 people so
far this year, are so feared that distance offers little consolation.
   In the Hindi language, ``kumbh'' means pot and ``mela'' means
fair. The festival's name is derived from a fight over a pot of
nectar.
   According to Hindu mythology, gods and demons were waging a war
of attrition when each side realized it needed nectar to achieve
immortality and victory. The nectar was hidden beneath an ocean, so
the combatants churned the waters. The pot of nectar flew out and
was seized by Vishnu, the god of creation, who fled across the
heavens.
   During Vishnu's flight, drops of nectar fell at 12 spots. Four of
the sites, including Allahabad, are in India, while the rest are in
heaven.
   Holy fairs are held at the three other Indian sites, but
Allahabad is considered the holiest site because it lies at the
confluence of three sacred rivers.
   The pilgrims will bathe in the Ganges and Yamuna. The Saraswati
is invisible to the human eye, but Hindu faithful believe it flows
under the ground.
   They also believe that if they bathe at the exact spot where the
nectar fell _ and at the most auspicious time _ they will receive
salvation from the birth cycle.
   Hindus believe every human is born and after death is reborn.
True salvation is when the human soul escapes this cycle and becomes
a higher being.
   The rush to the rivers has proved fatal in past years.
   More than 50 people died in a stampede in 1986 at a fair in
Hardwar, and in 1954, about 800 pilgrims died in a stampede at
Allahabad. The various holy sites conduct their festivals in
different years because of different planetary configurations.
   Other disasters have befallen the festivals. In 1760, about
18,000 people died at Hardwar in clashes between different Hindu
sects.
   ``In a big fair like this, you have no option but to leave
certain things to fate,'' said M.P. Ashnata, chief government
spokesman for Uttar Pradesh state. ``We can try to prevent a
stampede, but God forbid if it happens, what can you do?''
   On a more mundane level, authorities have tried to cope with
logistical problems by providing parking space for 200,000 vehicles
and docking space for 5,000 boats. At least 400 extra trains have
been routed to Allahabad.
   More than 10,000 tons of wheat, 4,000 tons of rice and 2,000 tons
of sugar have been stockpiled. Each day brings fresh deliveries of
13,000 gallons of milk, 10 tons of butter and five tons of cheese.
</TEXT>
