<FIRST>r a AM-AutoJointVentures     02-05 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Joint Ventures,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joint Ventures Wrap the Auto World a Little Tighter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two joint ventures with foreign automakers
announced by Chrysler Corp. last week are the latest in a group of
``strange bedfellow'' pairings that analysts say can be beneficial
to all involved.
   Chrysler Corp. last week announced it would hook up with Renault,
the French automaker, to make a mini sport-utility vehicle, code
named the ``JJ.'' Earlier in the week, the No. 3 U.S. automaker said
it would also sell Eagle sedans built in Canada by the South Korean
automaker Hyundai.
   They are the latest in a growing number of joint ventures by U.S.
and foreign automakers to market vehicles in the United States.
   ``There are a lot of marriages of convenience in this array,''
said analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York
City. ``You have some strange bedfellows.''
   Projects to produce cars and light trucks for the North American
market involve a variety of automakers and vehicles.
   _Later this year, Subaru and Isuzu, two Japanese companies, will
begin production of light trucks at a plant in Lafayette, Ind.
   _General Motors Corp. and Suzuki will begin making cars and
utility vehicles in Ingersoll, Ontario, within the next 18 months.
   _Ford Motor Co. and Nissan have plans to produce a minivan at an
expansion of Ford's Avon Lake, Ohio, plant in 1991.
   There are three joint ventures operating in the United States _ a
Mitsubishi-Chrysler plant in Normal, Ill., operated by Diamond-Star
Motors; a Mazda-Ford plant in Flat Rock, Mich., run by Mazda; and
the first joint venture, the GM-Toyota New United Motor
Manufacturing Inc. collaboration in Fremont, Calif.
   ``I think the key thing is what you have is a lot of these
players looking to find some means of utilizing capacity,'' analyst
Joseph Phillippi of Shearson Lehman Hutton said of joint ventures.
   Cheap labor costs in South Korea compared with the cost in the
United States is a major factor in some of the U.S. automaker
decisions.
   Ford's Festiva, Mitsubishi's Precis and Chevrolet's Lemans all
are made in South Korea.
   In Japan, Mitsubishi makes the Colt line for Chrysler, Isuzu
makes the Chevrolet Spectrum and Suzuki makes the Chevrolet Sprint.
   In the United States, the Flat Rock plant produces the MX-6 for
Mazda and the Probe for Ford. NUMMI makes a variety of small cars
for Toyota and GM. The Diamond-Star plant produces the Mitsubishi
Eclipse and Plymouth Acclaim, both two-seat sports cars.
   While the intertwining of the companies may be seem as orderly as
a plate of spaghetti, there are specific reasons why automakers get
involved in joint ventures with foreign companies.
   ``The risk is very low,'' Phillippi said. ``It's another guy's
plant, it's his overhead. In many cases there's very little that the
buyer has to put into tooling.''
   In return, the company providing the plant gets access to a
marketing and distribution system, and in some cases a dealership
network that helps sell the products.
   Phillippi said GM's Tracker is a perfect example of the
multinational vehicle. The small sport-utility vehicle will be sold
through GM's Geo franchises, from Suzuki's plant in Ingersoll,
Ontario.
   ``You have a Geo Tracker, built in Canada with basically Japanese
components, sold by a Chevrolet dealer,'' he said.
</TEXT>
