<FIRST>r i AM-RedNoses     02-05 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Red Noses,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Entertainers Launch Red Nose Day to Raise Money for Charity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top entertainers on Sunday launched Britain's
second Comic Relief Day campaign and predicted that 7 million people
will don red noses on March 10 in a day of national silliness to
help raise millions for charity.
   Organizers hope the campaign will top the $28 million raised last
year.
   Two-thirds of the money will go to projects in the Third World
run by Oxfam and the Save the Children Fund and the rest to programs
in Britain involving young people and the elderly.
   Rubber-faced comedian Rowan Atkinson appeared at the Criterion
Theater for the launch wearing a Comic Relief sweat shirt, T-shirt,
headgear and boxer shorts which are being sold through a clothing
store chain as part of the charity's fund-raising activites.
   Comedian Billy Connolly, who just returned from a 12-day trip to
Mozambique, said he was moved to tears by the plight of a young boy
orphaned when bandits butchered his parents. The boy and other
victims of Mozambique's guerrilla war need help from organizations
like Comic Relief, he said.
   Fellow comedian Stephen Fry said Red Nose Day 2 was intended to
be enjoyable but to have a serious side which would help people.
   This year's appeal has already involved the manufacture of 7
million red noses using 70 tons of red plastic donated by a
corporate sponsor, which kept one factory working three months.
   Other corporate sponsors have produced a Comic Relief mug,
written and designed Comic Relief postcards, and are organizing
competitions for vacations in Florida or Thailand. The pop group
Bananarama is also releasing a recording of The Beatles' song
``Help.''
   Between now and March 10, the campaign will try to sell the 7
million noses and other items to raise money for charity. Red Nose
Day 2 on March 10 will climax with a television spectacular,
organizers said.

</TEXT>
