<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-PrisonRiot     02-05 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Prison Riot,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eighteen Dead After Attempted Jail Break</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen prisoners died and eight others
were injured after they were jammed into a tiny cell in a punitive
action following an attempted jail break, authorities said Sunday.
   Several of the 18 died of asphyxiation, while others were
trampled to death by cellmates when more than 50 prisoners were
packed into a 3-by-9 foot cell with no window or ventilation, Sao
Paulo state prison system spokesman Guilherme Santana told The
Associated Press.
   One was shot to death, said Carlos Vasconcellos, who is in charge
of the Parque Sao Lucas jail where the incident occurred.
   The prisoners were forced into the cell after grabbing prison
guard Teresa Dantas in an early morning attempted break from the
jail, in a working-class neighborhood of Sao Paulo.
   ``The decision made by the police officer on duty to place so
many prisoners in a small cell was barbaric,'' Vasconcellos told The
Associated Press.
   The jail holds mostly petty criminals awaiting trial or transfer
to a state prison. By late afternoon, the surviving prisoners were
back in their regular cells, said Vasconcellos.
   According to Vasconcellos, the rebellion began at about 8:30 a.m.
when the guard, Ms. Dantas, opened a door to throw in two thieves.
   When she opened the door, 63 prisoners _ being held in an area
designed to hold 25 _ escaped onto the adjacent jail patio.
   Dantas was taken hostage until police managed to free her and
herd the majority of prisoners into the isolation cell, Vasconcellos
said. One prisoner was shot when the inmates were being moved to the
isolation cell, Vasconcellos said.
   ``They must have panicked in the small space,'' said
Vasconcellos, who arrived an hour later and ordered the prisoners
freed.
   Vasconcellos said the officer who ordered the jailing would be
subject to punitive measures.
</TEXT>
