<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Norway 1stLd-Writethru a0658 02-05 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Norway, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norwegian's Reported Comment on Nazis Causes Uproar</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 10th, ``Last week...'' to ADD Israeli raiding
villages and detaining residents. Pickup last graf, ``Israel created...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Norwegian U.N. officer has caused an uproar by
comparing Israeli soldiers to Nazis because of their expulsion of
Lebanese from villages in Israel's security zone in south Lebanon,
newspapers said Sunday.
   Timor Goksel, spokesman for the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon,
confirmed he had received a complaint about language used by Lt.
Col. J.E. Karlsen, commander of UNIFIL's Norwegian battalion.
   ``In World War II, my fellow countrymen sacrificed their lives in
the struggle against the Nazis who were trying to expel Jews from
Norway. Nowadays you behave in south Lebanon exactly as the Nazis
did,'' Karlsen was quoted as saying by the English-language
Jerusalem Post.
   The Post and Hebrew-language Haaretz said Karlsen made the remark
at a meeting Thursday with Israeli officers over recent
confrontations between the U.N. forces and Israeli troops in south
Lebanon.
   Haaretz said the Israeli army demanded Karlsen be removed from
his post. An army official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the army made no such demand but filed a protest. Goksel said the
peacekeepers are investigating.
   Rabbi Michael Malchior, chief rabbi in the Norwegian capital,
Oslo, said on Israeli radio that Norwegian Jews were ``very angry.''
He said the reported remark was part of a growing pattern of
anti-Jewish behavior.
   ``We're hearing of such things more and more, not only in
Norway,'' he said. ``It's very important to oppose this. The Jewish
community will respond in the strongest manner.''
   Israeli soldiers and UNIFIL troops have had several
confrontations over the deportation of Lebanese civilias from
Israel's self-declared security zone, which is patrolled by the
largely Christian militia and Israeli soldiers.
   At least 70 Lebanese were expelled in the past month.
   Last week, Lebanon told its U.N. ambassador to lodge a formal
complaint with the Security Council, stating the expulsions violate
international law.
   In addition, Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militiamen and
Israeli soldiers have raided villages in the security zone and
detained residents suspected of anti-Israeli activities, Goksel said.
   Israel created the six- to 10-mile-wide zone north of its border
when it withdrew most of its forces from Lebanon in 1985 after a
three-year occupation.
</TEXT>
