<HEAD>Supreme Court Scheduled Demjanjuk Appeal For November 1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Sunday rescheduled the
appeal of convicted Nazi war criminal John Demjanjuk for Nov. 1, the
Itim news agency said.
   Demjanjuk, a retired auto worker from Ohio, was sentenced to
death last year for crimes against humanity and against the Jewish
people committed during World War II.
   He was accused of being ``Ivan the Terrible,'' a guard who
terrorized and killed Jews at the Treblinka death camp in
German-occupied Poland. Demjanjuk claimed he was a victim of
mistaken identity.
   His appeal, originally scheduled to start in December, was
postponed for six months following the suicide of one of his defense
attorneys.
   The court agreed Sunday to a further extension, following a
request by his defense council, Yoram Sheftel. Sheftel said he has
not yet found anyone willing to replace the late Dov Eitan.
   Sheftel also said he is still suffering from an eye injury
inflicted in December, when an assailant hurled acid on his face
during Eitan's funeral. Many Israelis were angry that Sheftel agreed
to defend Demjanjuk.
