<FIRST>r i AM-Shevardnadze 1stLd-Writethru   02-05 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shevardnadze, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0677,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Said To Prepare For Meeting With Soviet Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with guerrillas reaching accord;
picks up 4th pvs: Soviet sources...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ISL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrilla leaders will meet
Monday with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze to discuss
ways to end Afghanistan's civil war, guerrilla sources said.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said leaders of
the seven-group guerrilla alliance hoped to present a united front
at the meeting.
   In Tehran, Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said the
Pakistan- and Iran-based guerrilla alliances signed an accord on
Sunday to cooperate on forming a new government.
   The agreement could boost the quarrelsome guerrilla factions'
chances of succeeding the communist regime in Kabul regime after the
Soviet troop withdrawal is completed.
   Soviet sources would neither confirm nor deny that Shevardnadze
would meet with the insurgent leaders.
   Hamed Karzai, a spokesman for the alliance, also refused to
confirm the talks.
   Shevardnadze arrived in the Pakistan capital early Sunday for
talks with government officials.
   ``The Soviet leadership has decided to consult with the
government of Pakistan on how best to contribute to restoring peace
and tranquility in Afghanistan,'' he said.
   ``Problems have been piling up. There are quite a few of them.''
   Pakistan has supported the insurgents in their 10-year civil war
against Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government and has allowed the
guerrillas to operate from Pakistani soil.
   Shevardnadze's diplomatic mission came as the deadline neared for
the Soviet Union's troop withdrawal from Afghanistan. The Soviets
are to be out by Feb. 15 under a U.N.-mediated accord.
   Shevardnadze originally was to depart Sunday, but Pakistani
officials said he extended his stay until late Monday morning.
   His car drove past lines of police as he arrived for talks with
his Pakistani counterpart, Sahabzada Yaqub Khan. He later sat down
to a working lunch with Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto and then met
with President Ghulam Ishaq Khan.
   Pakistan's government-run television said Bhutto accepted an
invitation to visit the Soviet Union. No date was set.
   Officials would not comment on the talks. They said the Soviet
minister would hold a news conference prior to his departure.
   The guerrillas, also known as mujahedeen, oppose a coalition
government that would include the ruling People's Democratic Party
of Afghanistan, which the Soviets back.
   The guerrilla alliance met with Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister
Yuli Vorontsov in January in Islamabad, and in December in the Saudi
Arabian resort city of Taif.
   Talks broke off after Vorontsov said the Afghan ruling party had
to be part of a postwar government or the Soviets would continue
their support of Afghan President Najib.
</TEXT>
