<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     02-05 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Brilliant Traces' Doesn't Live Up to Name</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Brilliant Traces,'' the latest play presented
by the Circle Repertory Company, fails to deliver on its name.
   The two-character play by Cindy Lou Johnson opened Sunday at the
off-Broadway Cherry Lane Theater. It's an hour and a half, without
intermission, originally developed at a summer seminar at Vassar.
   The situation has a young woman in a disheveled bridal gown barge
into a young man's cabin in a snowy, remote part of Alaska. Both are
fleeing human relationships. Joan Cusack is Rosannah and Kevin
Anderson is Henry.
   As they talk, sometimes shouting and crossing the line into
psychosis then quickly crossing back into calmer neurosis, they
reveal, drop by slow drop, the traumas which made them antisocial,
fearful and borderline crazy.
   For him, it was a beloved child who died at 2. For her, it was
her mother leaving when she was young, her father not showing love
and her father now old and so forgetful he doesn't know her.
   The play ends abruptly with Henry comforting Rosannah and the
implication that this is a solution for them.
   Terry Kinney, a founding member of Steppenwolf Theater Company in
Chicago, directs with the kind of stylized weirdness that works for
Sam Shepard.
   When a character runs around doing something off-the-wall in some
of Shepard's plays, a viewer thinks of the character, his own
relatives, the American West and the decline of civilization.
There's nothing that deep in this play.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
