<FILEID>AP-NR-02-05-89 1654EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Commonwealth-SAfrica     02-05 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commonwealth-SAfrica,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministers Consider Tougher Sanctions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers from eight British
Commonwealth nations gathered Sunday for a conference to propose
tougher economic sanctions against white-led South Africa.
   The ministers, beginning their meeting Monday, also plan to
discuss new ways for the 49-member Commonwealth _ former components
of the British empire _ to bolster poor black-ruled states
threatened by South African destabilization, organizers said.
   Britain is not a member of the committee because of Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher's opposition to sanctions. Thatcher
maintains black South Africans, and neighboring states, will suffer
most from tougher measures against the Pretoria government.
   Canadian External Affairs Minister Joe Clark, who arrived
Saturday in the Zimbabwean capital of Harare, will chair the third
three-day meeting of the so-called Commonwealth Committee of Foreign
Ministers on Southern Africa.
   ``Given the location of this meeting and the special
circumstances of the frontline states the committee has agreed that
destabilization be the theme of the Harare meeting,'' a statement
from the Canadian High Commission here said on the eve of the talks.
   Zimbabwe, South Africa's northern neighbor, is one of the six
``frontline states'' _ southern Africa countries that are in
confrontation with Pretoria over its racial policy of apartheid.
   The regional bloc, grouping also Angola, Botswana, Mozambique,
Tanzania and Zambia, spearheads African efforts for more
international pressure on Pretoria.
   It also seeks massive aid and investment for the fragile
economies of its members to counter South African economic and
military retaliation. Most frontliners are heavily dependent on
South Africa, economic powerhouse of the region, for trade and for
transport links with the outside world.
   Britain, Japan, the United States and West Germany are frequently
singled out by the frontline states for ignoring calls for tougher
sanctions. But the Commonwealth has little real muscle in
confronting South Africa without Mrs. Thatcher's support.
   The Southern Africa committee was formed by the 26th Commonwealth
summit in Vancouver, Canada, in 1987 to monitor sanctions and
propose ways of tightening the economic blockade against South
Africa to force that country to abandon its apartheid system. The
committee met twice last year, in the Zambian capital of Lusaka and
in Toronto, Canada.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 5 million whites virtually
control the economy and government and live mainly apart from the 26
million blacks, who have no vote in national affairs.
</TEXT>
