<FIRST>r i AM-AfghanRebels     02-05 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan Rebels,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebel Leaders Sign Pact of Cooperation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Afghan resistance based in
Iran and Pakistan on Sunday signed a pact to cooperate in a new
government in Afghanistan, Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said.
   Velayati told The Associated Press the accord was signed in
Tehran ``after a lot of effort'' during a meeting he held with two
leaders of the guerrillas, who call themselves mujahedeen, or holy
warriors.
   ``They finally signed an agreement for cooperation about a future
government for Afghanistan,'' Velayati said.
   He gave no details of the accord, which could boost the
guerillas' chances of succeeding the communist regime in Kabul after
the Soviet army leaves the country. The Red Army is supposed to be
out by Feb. 15.
   The mujahedeen are split into two groups, the minority Shiite
Moslem alliance based in Iran, and the larger Pakistan-based Sunni
coalition. The Pakistan-based guerrilla leader Sibghatullah
Mojaddidi signed the cooperation and friendship pact with Mohammad
Karim Khalili, spokesman for the Iran-based alliance.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said it was believed
the two groups agreed on the number of seats to be offered to Shiite
representatives in the 480-member Shura assembly.
   The Shura is a form of Moslem parliament expected to meet next
month to appont an interim government for Afghanistan following the
Soviet pullout.
   The quarrelsome mujahedeen coalitions bickered for weeks over the
proportional division of assembly seats.
   Mojaddidi later returned to Islamabad, Pakistan, where guerrilla
sources said Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze would meet
guerrilla leaders Monday.
   Tehran radio reported that visiting Soviet Deputy Foreign
Minister Yuli Vorontsov held talks with Velayati on Sunday that
stressed the importance of a peaceful transfer of power after the
Soviets withdraw.
   All sides involved agree on the need for a settlement that will
produce a broad-based government to succeed the ruling People's
Democratic Party, which seized power in a bloody 1978 coup.
   But the party's Marxist leader, President Najib, insists such a
government must retain some of his officials.
   The mujahedeen consider the communists traitors for requesting
Soviet military intervention in December 1979 and refuse to deal
with them.
   There are no immediate prospects for peace between the Kabul
government and the guerrillas armed by the United States, Pakistan
and other Islamic countries.
</TEXT>
