<FIRST>r a BC-Opera     02-05 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Opera,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Welsh National Opera Makes U.S. Debut</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Welsh National Opera brought a fresh-faced
yet traditional production of Verdi's ``Falstaff'' to the Brooklyn
Academy of Music for its American debut.
   The orchestra, conducted by Richard Armstrong, sounded
first-rate, as did the on-stage French horn player, and the cast of
the production directed by West Germany's Peter Stein contains
young, fresh voices.
   Particularly enjoyable were Donald Maxwell, whose robust voice
made Falstaff sound younger then we've ever heard, Suzanne Murphy as
Mistress Ford, Nuccia Focile as Nannetta, her daughter, and Laurence
Dale, who loves Nannetta.
   The Princess of Wales attended the first of four performances on
Thursday. Reviewers attended Saturday night.
   Realism winds is way through the staging. When the laundry basket
in which Falstaff hides is dumped out a window into a ditch, he can
be seen still in it, unlike some stagings that let him exit through
a trapdoor first.
   Later, Falstaff opens his shirt to reveal what looks like fat,
not pillows.
   Settings are sparse, and everything is used. Mistress Ford sits
on her only chair and plays a lute. With fluffy clouds behind her,
Nanette reclines on the sill of the picture window through which
Falstaff is later dumped.
   Orange and black planks form the interior walls of the Ford house
and the wall outside the tavern, the same colors in Mistress Ford
and Nannetta's dresses. When Ford's men create havoc searching for
Falstaff, they tear strips off the wall.
   In the tavern, Falstaff upends a table and, in a humorous touch,
takes out chalk and uses it as a blackboard. Stein has wisely
refrained from stuffing ``Falstaff'' with visual jokes.
   The stage is made small, giving the opera intimacy and projecting
voices.
   The tavern interior is shallow and the Ford living room not much
deeper. Only the Windsor Park scene uses the full width of the
stage. Even that has cast and chorus _ milling around nicely, never
static _ on a center raked platform for the finale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
