<FIRST>r a AM-GangViolence     02-05 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gang Violence,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arrest In Death Of 2-Year-Old, Two Others Die</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An alleged gang member has been arrested in
the drive-by shooting of a 2-year-old boy, whose funeral drew calls
to halt the persistent violence that left two other people dead
during the weekend.
   The violence came on the heels of an anti-gang sweep of
south-central Los Angeles late Friday and early Saturday. About 240
officers made 118 arrests. Seventy-one of those arrested were known
gang members, police said.
   More than 330 killings were attributed to gang violence in Los
Angeles County in 1988.
   Compton police announced Saturday the arrest of an 18-year-old
for investigation of the Jan. 28 shooting that killed Phillip
Fisher, 2, and DeAndre Richards, 19.
   The man's name was withheld because two other gang members were
being sought, Sgt. Danny Sneed said Sunday.
   The 18-year-old allegedly was in the assailant's car and might
have been the one who fired at least 20 rounds from a military-style
assault rifle into a group of people standing on a sidewalk, killing
Fisher and Richards, Sneed said. Three people were injured, none
seriously.
   About 200 people attended a funeral service for the boy Saturday.
   ``This community needs healing,'' said Pat Moore, a
representative for U.S. Rep. Mervyn Dymally, who urged mourners to
work for an end to gang violence.
   ``Stand strong because this can repeat itself if we don't get
busy,'' she said. ``These are our children doing this.''
   Elsewhere Saturday, a 19-year-old was critically wounded by a
shot to the head while waiting in his car at a stoplight in Carson,
Los Angeles County sheriff's Deputy Roger Hom said. The attacker
pulled up alongside and started a conversation before opening fire,
Hom said.
   Deputies also studied gang links in the death of an 18-year-old
whose body was found in a vacant lot in a Willowbrook neighborhood
known for gang activity, said sheriff's Sgt. Ernie Roop. That victim
was shot several times in the upper body, Roop said.
   Another 18-year-old died after being shot in the abdomen when a
gunman opened fire on alleged rival gang members at a Hancock Park
store, police said.
   Elsewhere, nine reputed gang members in their teens were booked
for investigation of attempted murder in the shooting of a teen-ager
in El Sereno, police said. The victim, described as a gang member,
was standing with friends in front of a house when he was shot in
the leg by someone driving past, Sgt. Tony Silva said.
   Others at the house drove off in pursuit and flagged down a
patrol car. Police later stopped two cars believed to have been
carrying gang members involved in the shooting, Silva said.
</TEXT>
