<FIRST>r a AM-CongressRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0716 02-05 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``At their...'' to delete extra word
`and'; picks up 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``But many...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Democrats, at Retreat, Dread Upcoming Decision on Pay Raise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE SULPHUR SPRINGS, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democrats tried to buck
up their courage Sunday as they wrapped up a weekend retreat and
looked toward Capitol Hill battles over a proposed 51 percent pay
raise.
   ``When we face re-election in 22 months, no one will be defeated
because of that issue,'' Rep. Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., chairman of the
House Democratic campaign committee, told his colleagues. ``When you
address the issue head-up, the people will understand it. We will
survive.''
   Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., appearing on CBS' ``Face the Nation,''
reminded the television audience four times that it was President
Reagan who proposed raising congressional salaries from $89,500 to
$135,000, and that President Bush endorsed it.
   However, Hoyer said House Speaker Jim Wright ``is confronted with
an environment atmosphere of a great deal of hypocrisy, very
frankly, as well as hysteria and demagoguery. Any time a pay raise
is before the Congress, there's a great deal of indignation and it's
hard for the Congress to deal with that issue.''
   At their weekend conference at the luxurious Greenbrier resort,
members tried to bowl, swim, ride, shoot, skate, drink, dance, talk,
eat, jog, putt, swing and pray their blues away.
   But many rank-and-file lawmakers said that while it was a great
family outing, it did not alleviate their dread of the looming pay
battle.
   ``We got the news this weekend that we've got an appointment for
a root canal every day this week,'' said Rep. Dick Durbin, D-Ill.,
who was among those hoping Wright would find a way to dispose of the
pay raise issue.
   ``I would like this execution to be swift. I don't want to bleed
to death,'' Durbin said, adding that 75 percent of his constituents
said in a survey they would consider the pay raise a major issue in
the next election.
   On ``Face the Nation,'' Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., said,
``This pay raise is an affront to the American people, both with
respect to the amount and, in particular, the method by which
Congress is going about trying to get this without ever having to
record a vote or hold itself accountable to the American people.''
   Under the law, the pay raise goes into effect for members of
Congress, federal judges, and top executive branch officials on
Wednesday unless both chambers of Congress have voted it down. The
Senate did so, 95-5, last Thursday, leaving the final decision with
the House.
   Wright said last week he would not schedule any vote until after
the pay was increased, but then would have the House vote on
reducing the pay increase to 30 percent.
   That increase would be equal to the amount of current pay plus
outside income from speaking fees and other honoraria that members
now may keep, but would be banned in the future under Wright's plan.
   Wright said Sunday he ``cannot guarantee that we'll be seen or
judged in the right light. Perhaps I can help us to act in the right
light _ with dignity and honor and self-respect.''
   There was no groundswell of support for the 30 percent solution
among the Democrats at the Greenbrier. A top leadership source said
there had been new discussions on whether to just kill the pay
raise, but the speaker's strategy had not changed.
   Many lawmakers _ both Democrats and Republicans _ had preferred
the original leadership strategy accepting the pay boost and
avoiding any votes. Wright's plan, which if approved would have to
be negotiated with the Senate, was seen as potentially dragging the
issue out for months.
   Some also worried they could lose both their pay raise and
honoraria income. Others disliked waiting until after the deadline
for the rollback, since federal judges would get to keep the whole
amount under a constitutional provision prohibiting their pay from
ever being reduced.
   ``There's a feeling that if we're all going to hang, we're going
to hang together,'' said Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif.
   Back in Washington, opponents of the pay raise planned Monday to
attempt to force embarrassing procedural votes on the House floor,
in an effort to force Wright to allow a pre-deadline roll call on
the issue. Numerous surveys have indicated that, if put to a vote,
the pay raise would be defeated.
   Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y., said he wasn't concerned about further
political fallout because of those insurgents.
   ``The issue already has embarrassed Congress about as much as we
can be embarrassed,'' he said.
</TEXT>
