<FIRST>r a AM-TampaDisturbance     02-05 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tampa Disturbance,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Of Troubled Neighborhood Hope Worst Is Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of a Tampa neighborhood rocked by
two nights of sporadic street violence said they are anxious to find
out why a black drug suspect died following a struggle with police.
   Officials say Edgar Allen Price, 40, died of heart failure caused
by asphyxiation after an undercover drug arrest Wednesday night.
Price's death triggered violence Wednesday and, to a lesser extent,
Thursday night in College Hill, a poor, predominantly black
neighborhood. One person was arrested Wednesday and nine on Thursday.
   The neighborhood was quiet Friday and Saturday nights.
   Forensic tests are being run to determine what caused Price, a
burly 6-foot-3, 300-pound suspected drug dealer, to stop breathing
after a violent struggle with eight police officers.
   Some residents of the College Hill neighborhood already have made
up their minds how Price, a convicted felon from Houston, died;
others haven't. But all want to know what the Hillsborough County
medical examiner's office has to say.
   Autopsy results are expected this week.
   ``I want to know how he died, what the autopsy says. Everybody
does,'' resident Marcellis Dismukes said Saturday. ``If I went into
the white Palma Ceia area I wouldn't want them to throw rocks and
bottles at me because I'm black. And it's wrong for the kids here to
do that to innocent people.''
   ``He was a dope dealer. He was not a righteous man. But that was
no reason to get him killed,'' said resident Twine Culpa.
   During the clash Wednesday, 50-75 young people, many ages 12 to
14, hurled debris at officers and passing motorists, torched and
looted a grocery store and fired two shotgun blasts into the side of
a news van.
   About 100 police in riot gear moved in swiftly, sealed off a
22-block area and restored calm.
   Police said Price resisted violently and officers used
nightsticks, handcuffs and leg manacles to subdue him. Thrown rocks
and bottles prevented paramedics from tending a bleeding head wound
at the scene, police said, so officers put Price in a cruiser and
drove about a block away, where medics could get to him.
   By then, less than a minute later, he was suffering breathing
problems, police said.
   Resident, Otis Bell, 51, said tensions have been smoldering since
the 1987 death of Melvin Hair, a black man who died after a
policeman responding to a domestic dispute applied a since-banned
choke hold to subdue him.
   Hair's death triggered several nights of street violence in
College Hill. Afterward, city officials worked with black leaders to
upgrade housing, provide jobs and better economic opportunities.
Progress has been slow, residents say.
</TEXT>
