<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-US     02-05 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-US,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Says Quayle Statements `Constructive'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega praised a U.S.
pledge to hold off military aid for rebels and proposed that the
United States join Central American governments to fight drug
trafficking, newspapers reported Sunday.
   Barricada, the government newspaper, quoted Ortega as saying Vice
President Quayle's promise and other comments on Nicaragua were
``constructive, intelligent, and not confrontational.''
   Quayle told reporters in Venezuela last week that the Bush
administration was ``going to give the diplomatic route a chance''
to resolve the 8-year war between the leftist Sandinista government
and U.S.-backed rebels.
   U.S. military aid to the Contras expired last year. Quayle
pledged the United States will not seek more aid in order to give
peace talks a chance, according to Costa Rican President Oscar Arias.
   They all were in Caracas, the Venezuelan capital, attending
Thursday's inauguration of President Carlos Andres Perez.
   Ortega did not meet Quayle but showed a new peace proposal to
former President Carter on Wednesday.
   Quayle criticized that meeting, telling reporters Thursday,
``Obviously when you have a former president meeting with heads of
state we don't meet with, it has a chance of complicating matters.''
   Ortega told Barricada none of Quayle's statements contained
``confrontational responses, including when (reporters) asked him
about my meeting with former President Carter.''
   The United States has refused to negotiate with Nicaragua, saying
the Sandinistas must first negotiate with their opposition.
   Ortega also said Nicaragua's Foreign Minister Miguel D'Escoto
will present a plan next week to the United Nations calling on the
United States to work with Central American governments to fight
drug trafficking, the pro-government El Nuevo Diario reported.
   ``It's well-known that Central America is used by the drug
traffickers as a staging ground from south to north,'' Ortega told
the newspaper, without providing any details of the plan.
   Ortega said the Feb. 13-14 summit of Central American presidents
in El Salvador would achieve tangible results for the stalled 1987
Central American peace plan.
   The Nicaraguan leader said he and the presidents of El Salvador,
Costa Rica, Guatemala and Honduras expect the summit to produce
``not a simple communique, but rather concrete and specific
actions.''
   The peace plan calls for cease-fires in Nicaragua, El Salvador
and Guatemala, political amnesties, democratization and bars
countries from allowing their territory to be used by insurgents
fighting another country.
</TEXT>
