<FIRST>r a AM-ABA-Kennedy     02-05 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ABA-Kennedy,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kennedy Urges Lawyers to Stand Up for the Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Supreme Court Justice Anthony M. Kennedy
called upon the nation's lawyers Sunday to stand up for ``the rule
of law'' against forces that he said threaten to corrode American
society.
   ``It's important that the lawyers of this country understand the
corrosive effect when the law is disobeyed,'' Kennedy said in a
speech to the American Bar Association. ``I'm concerned that time is
running out. You must understand the assault on the rule of law in
philosophical terms.''
   Kennedy, making his first speech to the ABA since taking his seat
on the high court a year ago, did not offer specific examples of a
breakdown in law and order.
   But he said he is concerned by those who use poverty as a
justification for law-breaking.
   ``The rule of law is the only sure way to preserve human
dignity,'' he said. ``We have a legitimate legal and moral right to
enforce the criminal law.''
   Kennedy, who taught constitutional law at McGeorge School of Law
in California for 23 years, devoted much of his speech to an
examination of the historical and theoretical underpinnings of the
U.S. legal system.
   He said that system is founded on the consent of the governed and
survives because of its guarantee of individual rights.
   Among those rights is that of holding property, Kennedy said. ``I
know of no society that has protected human rights without
protecting property rights,'' he said.
   He also denounced the theory of the class struggle that is at the
heart of communism.
   ``Leninism, the class struggle, is absolutely antithetical to the
rule of law,'' Kennedy said.
   Two other members of the Supreme Court are attending the ABA's
mid-winter convention here.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist planned to address the ABA's
House of Delegates on Monday. The group is the policy-making body
for the association, the nation's largest organization of lawyers.
   Justice Byron R. White, a native of Colorado, was presented with
a portrait Sunday by the Colorado and Denver Bar Associations.
   The House of Delegates convenes Monday to consider several
controversial porposals, including an endorsement of gay rights
legislation.
   The proposal would urge enactment of laws to prohibit
discrimination based on sexual orientation. A similar proposal was
defeated narrowly by the delegates in 1985.
   The group also plans to vote on a package of proposals affecting
the insurance industry. The key provision would endorse federal
regulation of the industry and repeal a 1945 law granting the
industry broad exemption from federal antitrust violations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
