<FIRST>r a AM-BoxcarRefugees     02-05 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boxcar Refugees,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadorans Found Leaving Boxcar In Kansas City; Two Hospitalized</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cold Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Salvadoran immigrants were in a
hospital for treatment of frostbite Sunday after riding in a boxcar
for 2{ days with only some blankets and a frozen gallon of milk.
   The two women, and four others from El Salvador, were discovered
Friday, when they left a boxcar in a North Kansas City railroad yard.
   The five women and one man, who spoke only Spanish, said they had
been riding the train in an attempt to reach a relative and possible
work in Washington, D.C.
   ``They were just froze,'' said Ida Barry, assistant manager of a
restaurant near the rail yard. ``Cold isn't even the word for it.''
The city had below zero temperatures Friday and the high was only 5
degrees.
   Juana Isabel Duarte, 38, and Lorena Parada, 21, were listed in
fair condition Sunday at Truman Medical Center with frostbite of
their feet and legs.
   Another woman was released after treatment. She and the three
others were staying with a Kansas City woman while they wait for
their traveling companions to be released from the hospital.
   Speaking through an interpreter, the Salvadorans said Saturday
they were fleeing poverty and fighting in their violence-torn
Central American nation.
   They said they hoped to get jobs and earn enough money to buy
food for their children, who were left behind with friends and
relatives. Among them, they said, they left 15 children in El
Salvador.
   Only the man in the group, who asked that his name not be printed
for fear of political reprisals, has a U.S. work permit.
   No information about the women's legal status was available.
Attempts to reach Immigration and Naturalization Service officials
by telephone over the weekend were unsuccessful.
   The six ranged in ages from 21 to 38, according to an interpreter
and hospital officials. The group includes the man, his wife, her
sister, his sister and two unrelated women.
   They said they had been traveling 31 days.
   Three of the women said their husbands had been killed or had
disappeared within the last two years in El Salvador.
   The six were found Friday by Kenneth Bishop, a special agent for
the Norfolk &amp; Western Railway Co.
   Bishop, who said he was prohibited from talking to reporters,
spent nearly three hours on the phone Friday, trying to locate
immigration or social services agencies to help the Salvadorans,
witnesses said.
   Eventually he reached the Don Bosco Community Center, where
assistant director Marilyn Anson sent Spanish-speaking caseworker
Toni Valdez to the rail yard.
   ``We're not trying to mess with immigration or make a political
statement,'' Ms. Anson said. ``We're just trying to do the
humanitarian thing.''
   When Ms. Valdez first encountered the Salvadorans, she said they
could hardly walk.
   ``The (Don Bosco) Center wasn't open, and I didn't know what to
do with them, so I just brought them to my house,'' she said. ``One
by one, I had them all take a bath, and when they came out I saw
their toes were swollen and black and blue. That's when we got them
to the emergency room.''
   ``I don't know what will happen to them from now on,'' Ms. Valdez
said. ``They hope to wait here until the women are out of the
hospital. And then, some way, find the funds to continue on to
Washington.''
</TEXT>
