<FIRST>r i AM-Venezuela-Castro     02-05 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela-Castro,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Castro Says Cuba Ready For Latin America Political Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fidel Castro on Sunday defended his
30-year rule and said Cuba is ready to return to Latin American
political sphere.
   Culminating four days of effusive demonstrations of warmth and
support from Venezuelans who flocked to glimpse him wherever he
appeared, Castro spoke to a packed auditorium of journalists.
   ``I think my visit to Caracas for the first time in 30 years
shows that Cuba is ready, and Latin America is ready, for our
reintegration,'' said Castro.
   He visited Venezuela last in 1959, shortly after he seized power.
Relations between the countries quickly were strained when Castro
supported guerrillas trying to topple Venezuela's elected government
in the 1960s and early 1970s.
   Castro did not mention this support. All questions were submitted
beforehand, and Castro did not answer them all.
   He repeated his position that Cuba, if invited, would join the
Organization of American States.
   He said his visit to Caracas for the inauguration of Carlos
Andres Perez as Venezuela's president, along with visits to Peru and
Mexico for similar inaugurals last year, shows Cuba is being
accepted back into Latin American circles.
   ``Before I never got invited. Now I get invited,'' Castro said.
   He defended his length of time in power, the longest of any Latin
American dictator, saying he has less power inside Cuba then other
world leaders in their own countries.
   ``If you want to measure power, a U.S. president can start a
nuclear war without asking anybody,'' said Castro.
   He attacked the United States for its role in Latin America, but
praised the State Department for describing as worth studying a
recent proposal by El Salvadoran guerrillas to lay down their
weapons in exchange for a role in general elections.
   ``It's a sign of a better political will in the new Bush
administration'' said Castro.
</TEXT>
