<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay-Media     02-05 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay-Media,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspapers, Radio Banned Under Stroessner Return</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Paraguay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paraguay's most popular radio station,
its biggest daily newspaper and a weekly known for irreverent
commentary plan to reopen now that Gen. Alfredo Stroessner has been
ousted from power.
   All were ordered closed by President Stroessner for various
reasons during the past five years, or harassed out of existence.
   ``Today we are free. We don't have equipment, we don't have news
teletypes, we don't have our own phones, but it feels great,'' said
Humberto Rubin, director of Radio Nanduti at the station's rundown
office.
   ``We want to keep going little by little, the same way democracy
is advancing in Paraguay,'' he said.
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez, commander of the powerful First Army
Corps, unseated Stroessner in a short, unexpected and violent coup
Thursday night and Friday morning. On Sunday, Stroessner was flown
to exile in Brazil.
   On Sunday, Rodriguez told reporters, ``I'm going to guarantee all
freedoms and total democracy.''
   Rubin _ and the directors of the daily newspaper ABC Color and
the weekly El Pueblo _ say they will take Rodriguez' word.
   ``We will demand that the words pronounced by Gen. Rodriguez .. .
become a reality,'' Rubin told listeners in his first broadcast
since he was forced off the air in January 1987.
   Rubin suspended operations when a strange jamming signal the
government said it could not identify came on whenever he broadcast
news or views the government didn't like. The signal eventually came
on most every time he appeared on the air, and finally during the
ads of local businesses who eventually withdrew their sponsorship.
   Rubin's debut Sunday was not without glitches. He battled
technical problems, unsuccessfully struggling to set up connections
for on-air interviews and at times playing music to cover up for
faulty microphones.
   ``The station may be falling to pieces, but its desire to
transmit is whole,'' he told an interviewer.
   ABC Color, which parlayed investigative journalism into a
circulation of 75,000, was closed outright in March 1984 for
allegedly provoking class hatred.
   The next edition will appear in about 30 days, said owner Aldo
Zuccolillo. Already, the editorial staff is swelling and the long
dormant newsroom beginning to bustle.
   El Pueblo is a feisty weekly newspaper published by the
Revolutionary Febrerista Party. It was shut down in August 1987,
accused of showing lack of respect for authority.
   Editor Raimundo Careaga says the paper will hit the streets
Tuesday.
   Before it was banned, El Pueblo published cartoons depicting
Stroessner as a decrepit dinosaur, his interior minister as a devil
with fangs dripping blood, and the Cabinet as a passal of raucous
schoolboys.
</TEXT>
