<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Stroessner     02-05 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Stroessner,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deposed President Granted Only Temporary Asylum</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Paraguay, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Alfredo Stroessner, the
deposed dictator of Paraguay, has been granted temporary asylum in
Brazil but there is no limit on how long he can stay, officials said.
   Stroessner arrived Sunday evening in Campinas, 290 miles
southwest of Rio, on a Paraguay Airlines Boeing 707 flight with
about 20 family members and aides aboard from the Paraguayan capital
of Asuncion, officials said.
   The group was then taken by a Brazilian air force plane to the
small town of Itumbiara in the central Brazilian state of Goias.
   The Foreign Ministry said they were to spend the night in a guest
house owned by the government-run Furnas electric company, which
owns a hydroelectric power plant on the nearby Parnaiba river.
   A Foreign Ministry source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Stroessner owns property in the Itumbiara area and was to stay
in the guest house ``only temporarily.'' It was not known where
Stroessner would go after leaving the Furnas residence.
   The Foreign Ministry said the group included Stroessner's his son
and daughter-in-law, security guards, a Brazilian diplomat and
several other unidentified people.
   Although Stroessner, 76, eventually will have to find a permanent
home in another country, no limit was put on how long he might
remain in Brazil, said Jose Roberto Pinto, chief of the Brazilian
Embassy's political section in Asuncion.
   Stroessner, who ruled for 34 years, was derposed by his former
top commander, Gen. Andres Rodriguez, during a coup that began late
Thursday and reportedly left up to 300 dead.
   In an official note released by the Foreign Ministry Sunday,
Brazil said Paraguay had requested that Stroessner be granted asylum.
   ``In response to a request from the Paraguayan government, Brazil
has received the former President Alfredo Stroessner as a political
exile,'' the note released in federal capital of Brasilia said.
``The decision follows from Brazil's tradition of respecting the
right to political asylum and the norms on the subject set by
international law.''
   Press reports earlier speculated, Stroessner and his group could
be heading for the Atlantic coastal resort of Guaratuba in the
Brazilian state of Parana, where he owns a summer home.
   But Parana state governor Alvaro Dias told the Associated Press
he had received no notification from the Brazilian government of
Stroessner's arrival.
   ``I will be very sorry if Stroessner intends to set up residence
in Parana,'' Dias said from the state capital of Curitiba. ``We have
traditionally received political exiles fleeing from Stroessner's
34-year regime. We don't repudiate Stroessner as a human being but
for what he represents.''
</TEXT>
