<FILEID>AP-NR-02-05-89 2047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-France     02-05 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-France,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Envoy Makes First High-Level French Visit In Decade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian President Ali Khamenei conferred
Sunday with French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas, the first visit to
Tehran by a senior French official since the Islamic revolt a decade
ago, Tehran radio reported.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Dumas as saying,``I have
come to Tehran in hopes of improving relations between our two
countries to a desirable level.''
   Khamenei confirmed the possibility of establishing ``good, strong
relations, rooted in the historical ties between the two countries.''
   But newspaper and radio commentaries blasted French foreign
policy, pointing out that after the Soviet Union, France was Iraq's
second most important arms supplier.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Nicosia, said Dumas also met with Parliament Speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani, believed to be the architect of Iran's new open-door
policy.
   Rafsanjani said that good ties between Tehran and Paris were
possible, adding that France's ``adoption of just stands at
international forums could be effective in furthering bilateral
ties,'' the Iranian news agency said.
   Dumas is due in Geneva Tuesday to address the opening session of
the 40-nation disarmament conference which is negotiating a
comprehensive ban on chemical weapons.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency said earlier that Dumas and his
60-member delegation were met by Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati on arrival at Mehrabad Airport.
   Dumas was expected to seek French participation in Iran's
reconstruction projects after the Aug. 20 cease-fire that halted its
devastating war with neighboring Iraq.
   Also on the agenda is a long-running dispute over a $1 billion
loan made by the late Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi before the
overthrow of the monarchy in 1979.
   Iran has demanded that France repay the loan plus interest
amounting to an additional $1 billion. France has agreed to pay the
initial amount in installments, but not the interest.
   French relations with Iran faltered after the overthrow of the
pro-Western monarchy. Diplomatic ties were severed in July 1987,
after a police siege of the Iranian embassy in Paris where a
translator wanted for questioning in connection with terrorist
bombings had taken refuge.
   Relations were restored 11 months later after the translator,
Wahid Gordji, appeared for a brief interrogation, and pro-Iranian
extremists freed French hostages held in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
