<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     02-05 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader Warns About Country's Possible Economic Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Stipe Suvar has
warned that the country may collapse unless it makes an economic
turnaround soon, the state news agency Tanjug reported Sunday.
   Addressing a meeting of young party activists and students
Saturday, Suvar said the country's main concern was how to check
spiraling inflation which last month hit 290 percent.
   ``Unless the galloping inflation is stopped this year, the
economy may collapse causing social explosion and catastrophic
consequences'' Tanjug quoted him as saying.
   Living standards have plummeted to half their level since 1980,
and long lines have been forming to purchase the cheap dark bread
that bakeries sell during the early morning hours.
   In addition, Yugoslavia owes $21 billion to foreign creditors and
has a 17 percent unemployment rate.
   Last week, the divided party leadership held a three-day session
but again failed to agree on how to heal the country's worsening
political and economic ills, despite warnings from the military that
it might become active in resolving the crisis.
   Suvar told the meeting Saturday that the party session ``should
have cut short all quarrels and social arguments.''
   ``All problems can be solved only if there is no bloodshed on a
nationalist basis,'' Politika Ekspres, a Belgrade daily, quoted him
as saying.
   The main clash at the session, which ended Wednesday, occurred
between factions advocating greater political pluralism and more
democracy and those favoring increased central party control to
overcome Yugoslavia's worst crisis.
</TEXT>
