<FIRST>r i AM-Czecholsovakia-Havel     02-05 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czecholsovakia-Havel,0294</SECOND>
<UNK>Detained Dissident Thanks Supporters for Solidarity</UNK>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vaclav Havel, Czechoslovakia's best known
dissident, praised hundreds of people who signed a letter appealing
to the government to release him, his brother said Sunday.
   ``I am greatly moved and strengthened by these statements and
expressions of solidarity,'' Havel, 52, said in a brief message read
by telephone from Prague by his brother Ivan.
   ``It is not only important for me, but this also signifies the
increase of independent spiritual attitude and the growing of civil
courage in our society,'' the message said.
   Ivan Havel declined to say how the message reached him from the
dissident, detained in a prison in the country's capital.
   Havel, a banned playwright and a political theorist, has been
held since he and two other activists were arrested at a Jan. 16
rally
   Czechoslovak intellectuals sent a letter to Premier Ladislav
Adamec last month asking for the release of Havel and also urging
authorities to open talks immediately with independent groups and
disillusioned youths.
   The letter has been signed by at least 1,000 people to date. It
said the signers were ``disturbed and offended'' by the way
Czechoslovakia's official media reported on demonstrations in Prague
marking the death of Jan Palach, a student who burned himself to
death to protest the Soviet-led invasion in August 1968.
   In Warsaw, Poland, the National Executive Commission of the
banned trade union Solidarity on Sunday called on Czechoslovak
authorities to release all political prisoners, specifically naming
Havel, and begin talks with independent groups.
   Solidarity begins talks with Poland's communist government Monday.
   Havel has participated in meetings between Polish and
Czechoslovak intellectuals at undisclosed locations along the border
between the two countries.
