<FILEID>AP-NR-02-05-89 2230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Slowdown     02-05 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Slowdown,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industrial Output Down in January, But in Wrong Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrial output fell nearly 11 percent in
January from one month earlier in the sharpest drop since the
government began its austerity drive last fall, an official report
said Sunday.
   However, the drop was concentrated in areas where critical
shortages already exist _ energy, steel and raw materials _ as well
as daily commodities such as cotton, the Xinhua News Agency said.
   This will ``pose a threat to industrial development in the next
few months,'' it said. Many factories already are forced to shut
down two to four days a week because of shortages of energy and raw
materials such as steel, items whose production the government wants
expanded.
   Production of color televisions, refrigerators and other
household appliances was up, the report said, but gave no figures.
   Xinhua said industrial output totaled $26 billion in January,
down 10.9 percent from December but up 8.2 percent from January
1988. The government has said it wants to cut industrial growth to
about 10 percent this year, down from 17.7 percent for all of 1988.
   The government has blamed the rapid growth of the past few years
for inflation that economists privately peg at about 40 percent.
Officials said prices rose 18.5 percent in 1988, but also said in
October that the price index was up 26 percent over the previous
October.
   As the spiraling prices triggered public discontent, authorities
ordered cuts in September in bank loans, capital construction and
local government spending as anti-inflation moves.
   They also tried to control in the mushroom-like growth of small
rural factories, which now number more than 15 million. They have
both siphoned raw materials and energy away from larger, state-run
factories and put the state-run factories to shame with their
greater productivity.
   But local authorities have tried to shield their lucrative
factories from the impact of the new tight-money policy, and Xinhua
said rural industry actually increased output by 25 percent in
January over December.
   It said rural factories accounted for one-eighth of January's
total industrial output. State-owned factories increased output by
an average of 3.7 percent, Xinhua said.
   As the austerity policies begin to take effect, some economists
have worried that they will result in stagnant economic growth plus
inflation, experienced in many Western countries in the 1970s.
</TEXT>
