<FIRST>r a AM-TakeshitaVisit     02-05 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Takeshita Visit,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Prime Minister Visits Elderly Immigrants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT JABLON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita
thanked elderly Japanese immigrants Sunday for helping pave the way
for his country's rise as a world power, and offered $8,000 of his
own money to rebuild their earthquake-shattered retirement home.
   A smiling Takeshita spoke warmly in Japanese to more than 100
elderly residents, many holding small Japanese and American flags,
at the Japanese Retirement Home, a non-profit facility in heavily
Hispanic Boyle Heights east of the Little Tokyo district.
   ``He said America and Japan will become closer friends,''
translated Jim Yamasaki, a clerk at the home. ``He said: `We owe it
all to the Isei (first-generation immigrants). You are the pioneers,
the people who built the foundation on which Japan stands.'''
   Takeshita referred to Japan's strength in commerce and its
success in exports to the United States, said Michio Katsumata of
The Nihon Keizai Shimbun, a Japanese economic journal.
   The prime minister praised the good citizenship of
Japanese-Americans _ despite what he called their ``hard times''
during World War II when many were interned in camps _ as
contributing to Japan's strong relationship with America, Katsumata
said.
   ``It was nothing political ... a soft, gentle message to the old
people,'' Yamasaki said.
   Takeshita also presented a white-wrapped parcel that, according
to translators, he said contained his ``pocket money'' or ``spending
money.''
   It contained 1 million yen, about $8,000, apparently of the prime
minister's own money, said Edwin Hiroto, chief executive officer of
Keiro Services, which runs the home.
   The money will help fund construction of a 154-bed wing being
built to replace another wing damaged in the October 1987 Whittier
earthquake, Hiroto said.
   Takeshita arrived in Los Angeles Friday night after a Washington
visit with President Bush at which he declared Japan's intention to
broaden its involvement in international affairs.
   He is scheduled to meet with former President Ronald Reagan on
Monday before departing for Japan.
   Security was lavish at the center. Dozens of motorcycle officers
lined the block fronting the auditorium where Takeshita spoke.
   During a 45-minute visit conducted in Japanese, Takeshita was
greeted by a 105-year-old resident of the home, Mamoru Eto, who
fought in Japan's turn-of-the-century war with Russia.
   Residents bowed together, then offered a nostalgic song about
one's hometown, and another about orange blossoms.
   ``They're songs they remember from their childhood,'' Hiroto said.
   The prime minister thanked the chorus for bringing back memories
of songs he remembered from his childhood, also.
</TEXT>
