<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Satellite     02-05 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Satellite,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stay Tuned: Satellite TV Arrives in Britain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Satellite television beamed directly into British
homes for the first time on Sunday, but only a small fraction of
viewers could tune in.
   At 6 p.m., all four channels of publisher Rupert Murdoch's Sky
Television began broadcasting signals bounced off the Astra
satellite parked in orbit above central Africa.
   Murdoch boasts he's bringing American-style ``competition, choice
and quality'' to British television, which has only four land-based
channels _ two commercial and two operated by the state-financed
British Broadcasting Corp.
   ``I watch a lot of television in America and I enjoy it, much
more than coming here late at night and turning on snooker,'' he
told a news conference. Coverage of the game snooker is one of the
few available nighttime programs in Britain.
   Sky News kicked off with a newscast featuring what it said were
two world exclusives, a report on Britons selling their kidneys and
a cancer scare for a convicted murderess.
   The sports channel led off with Davis Cup tennis, ``Project X''
was the first movie shown on Sky Movies, and Sky Channel, the light
entertainment channel, began with a 30-minute feature on the birth
of Sky Television.
   No one knows for certain exactly how many viewers were able to
watch Sunday's launch.
   The government says only 7,000 people have the licenses needed to
operate satellite-receiving dishes from their homes, out of a
population of 56 million. Sky Television says thousands more can
receive some, or all, of the channels on cable.
   Dish manufacturers say it will be weeks, if not months, before
they can supply stores with the equipment. But Murdoch said within
three months stores would be receiving 100,000 dishes a month.
   Murdoch said the subscription channels need to attract about 1.5
million viewers before they start making money.
</TEXT>
