<FIRST>u a AM-MardiGras 3rdLd-Writethru a0778 02-05 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mardi Gras, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0778,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mardi Gras Helps Blind Revelers Deal With Crowds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf, `The parades' with one graf to add description
of Billy Crystal's participation.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NU2, NU3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They couldn't see the gaudy floats in the
Mardi Gras parade or the plastic beads and aluminum doubloons flung
toward them Sunday, but the group from the Louisiana Center for the
Blind had a blast.
   ``It's a lot of fun. Time just to cut loose and anything goes,''
said Ernestine Morais, of Central, Calif.
   The 15 adult students and seven staff members _ two sighted who
drove the vans _ were only a few of the thousands who lined parade
routes in cold, gray weather to see the 11 parades rolling through
metropolitian New Orleans on Sunday.
   The parades included the popular Bacchus, which named comedian
Billy Crystal as this year's god of wine and revelry. He threw
double handfuls of doubloons at the sea of arms below him, stopping
only to pull out a camera to make home videos of the crowd.
   There was a serious purpose to the school's trip, said center's
director, Joanne Fernandez. That was helping students learn to
navigate through crowds, she said.
   ``This is one of our biggest confidence builders,'' Fernandez
said. ``Mardi Gras is the ultimate. If you can travel through a
Mardi Gras crowd, you can go through any crowd and you can go to any
place.''
   It was cloudy and drizzling Sunday with temperatures in the 40s.
Near freezing temperatures were predicted overnight, getting a
little colder Monday and Fat Tuesday, said the National Weather
Service.
   Parade-watchers bundled up but enjoyed themselves. Sometimes,
people in the blind group would take off their heavy gloves to
search for a string of beads or other parade baubles.
   The group had staked out a spot right behind the police
barricades on the street's median. Like the sighted people around
them, they were grabbing for the plastic beads, doubloons and other
trinkets.
   ``This is the kind of souvenir shopping I can afford,'' said Ms.
Morais.
   When a doubloon clanged on the street in front of the barricade,
long white canes poked out toward it, sweeping the street until one
touched the coin and pulled it in. Beads hit the ground and several
people quickly knelt, their hands sweeping around until one person
called out, ``I have it!''
   Some sighted people in the crowd took their own beads and tossed
them into the little group. Others reached through the groping hands
to grab beads for themselves.
   The crowd surged into the French Quarter between parades, ready
to rock on Bourbon Street.
   One rider in an afternoon parade was injured and knocked
unconscious for several minutes when he fell from a float and hit
his head and shoulder, said police spokesman John Bryson. It was the
weekend's second parade-related injury.
   New Orleans police estimated this will be the biggest Mardi Gras
ever, with 1.7 million revelers lining the streets and jamming the
French Quarter on Fat Tuesday, the last blowout before the solemn
season of Lent. Authorities said 1.5 million people attended the
1988 celebration.
   The long Carnival weekend got under way Saturday, highlighted by
the ``super parade'' of Endymion with celebrity riders, pop singers
Daryl Hall and John Oates and child television star Fred Savage of
``The Wonder Years,'' on giant, animated floats.
</TEXT>
