<SECOND>AM-Crack Killing,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Marshal: Dispute Over Crack Use Leads To Fatal Torching Of Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man died Sunday after his wife doused him with
paint thinner and set him on fire during an argument the couple were
having over her alleged use of crack, said a Fire Department
spokesman.
   Gary Tate, 41, died at New York Hospital, where he was taken
after the torching Saturday in the hallway outside their Brooklyn
apartment, said the spokesman, John Mulligan.
   Tate's wife, Jessie, 38, was also at the hospital with burns to
the right hand and arm suffered during the 6 p.m. incident at a
housing project, he said. She was placed under guard at the
hospital's burn center, where she was listed in stable condition.
   She was charged by the fire marshal's office with second-degree
attempted murder, second-degree arson and second-degree assault,
Mulligan said. It was expected that the charges against her would be
upgraded to reflect Tate's death, he said.
   ``Their whole dispute was about her alleged smoking (of) crack,''
Mulligan said.
   Mrs. Tate apparently became so enraged during the argument that
she doused her husband ``from head to foot'' and ignited a rolled up
paper bag, which she used as a torch to set him on fire as they
stood in the hallway, Mulligan said.
   The husband ran into their apartment, where he jumped into the
bathtub and turned on the water to put out the flames, but not
before the fire caused burns over 96 percent of his body, the
spokesman said.
   He said Mrs. Tate's injuries were caused when she accidentally
spilled a small amount of paint thinner on herself while pouring it
over her husband.
