<HEAD>Character Actor William Forrest Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Forrest, a former star
athlete who appeared in nearly 200 films and on television's ``The
Adventures of Rin Tin Tin,'' has died at age 86.
   Forrest, who died Jan. 29, often played the pleasant but stern
military officer in World War II films.
   He appeared in nearly 200 films over 30 years, including ``Here
Comes Mr. Jordan,'' ``Miracle on 34th Street'' and ``They Died With
Their Boots On.'' His last feature was believed to be ``The Marriage
of a Young Stockbroker'' in 1971.
   A standout athlete at Princeton University, Forrest began acting
in 1938 at the Pasadena Playhouse and the next year made his first
motion picture, ``Lone Wolf Meets Lady.''
   For many years, he averaged five or more films a year.
   He also played the fort commander on television's ``The
Adventures of Rin Tin Tin'' from 1954 to 1959.
   Forrest is survived by his wife, Wilhelmina, two sons, a daughter
and four grandchildren.
</TEXT>
