<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     02-05 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discovery Crew Arrives For Delayed Mission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crew of the shuttle Discovery,
whose mission has been delayed until mid-March, arrived at Kennedy
Space Center Sunday to participate in a practice countdown.
   Meanwhile, workers at the launch pad prepared to replace
turbopumps in the shuttle's three main engines. They also struggled
to make Discovery's cargo, a $100 million satellite, fit into the
payload bay.
   The five astronauts swooped over the space center in T-38
military jets and touched down at the shuttle runway Sunday
afternoon.
   Sunny skies and temperatures in the 80s greeted the astronauts,
who wriggled out of their heavy flight jackets as soon as they
climbed out of the two-seater jets.
   Shuttle commander Michael Coats commended the efforts of
engineers and technicians who are replacing the three high-pressure
oxygen turbopumps, which they fear could crack and cause an
explosion in flight.
   The turbopumps were manufactured by the same process as one
turbopump on the shuttle Atlantis, which cracked during the December
shuttle mission.
   Investigators blamed moisture for that crack and recommended that
Discovery turbopumps be replaced as a safety precaution.
   The decision to replace the turbopumps forced NASA to delay
Discovery's flight, which originally would have taken off last week.
   ``We know how hard everbody's been working and how much work
there is to do, and we certainly appreciate all the work that is
being done.'' Coats told reporters gathered at the shuttle runway.
   Within an hour, Coats and his crew had taken a practice drive in
a small armored tank designed to evacuate the launch pad in an
emergency.
   Coats and shuttle pilot John E. Blaha then boarded a shuttle
training jet for landing practice.
   Monday's activities include emergency escape drills at the launch
pad. Tuesday morning, Coats, Blaha and mission specialists Robert C.
Springer, James F. Buchli and James P. Bagian will board Discovery
for a dress rehearsal of launch morning.
</TEXT>
