<HEAD>Spooked Elephant Takes Riders On Wild Ride</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 4-ton elephant broke loose from a
petting zoo at the Southwest Florida Fair, tore through a crowded
midway and plunged into a lake with three terrified riders aboard.
   ``We were afraid he was going to kill us _ stomp on us,'' said
Consolacion Cruz of Alva, who clutched her 4-year-old godson and his
18-year-old aunt on the wild ride Saturday.
   The 15-year-old female elephant used for paid rides apparently
became spooked and bolted from the zoo. That sent fairgoers
scambling to get out of the animal's way.
   At least eight people were sent to local hospitals with minor
back injuries and grease burns from toppled concession stands.
   After the elephant plunged into the midway lake, spilling its
riders, the animal jumped from the water and lumbered onward,
crashing into more concession stands.
   Carl Patinella, 48, of New Jersey, never saw the elephant
barreling toward his fried dough stand, named ``Elephant Ears.''
   ``If I'd seen it coming I probably would've had a heart attack,''
Patinella said. ``He almost turned the stand over.'' Patinella's
wife suffered burns on her arms from the hot grease that sloshed
from the fryer, and Patinella wrenched his back in the sudden jolt.
   Joe Frisco, an elephant caretaker, managed to grab a chest strap
and slow the elephant until she trampled on a water tube. A gyser of
water shot skyward, spooking the elephant once more. And the chase
was on again as she crashed into a corn dog stand. Finally, Frisco
was able to stop the animal and guide her back to the corral.
   Speculating about the cause of Kelly's rampage, Frisco said,
``She had to be hit with a pellet gun or something. She'd never done
this before in 15 years.''
   Ms. Cruz, who slipped below the surface of the lake four times
and lost consciousness had to be rescued, but her 4-year-old godson,
Pascual Cortez, and the child's aunt, Lucy Hernandez, were able to
swim to shore safely.
</TEXT>
