<FIRST>u f AM-GlobalReservations 1stLd-Writethru   02-05 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Global Reservations, 1st Ld-Writethru,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>American, Delta Announce Partnership To Market Global Reservations
Network</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs with further details.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines and American Airlines announced
Sunday they were joining their global computerized reservations
under a new partnership.
   Under the agreement, each airline will contribute its existing
system to the new joint venture _ American's SABRE and Delta's DATAS
II. Delta, whose system is the smaller of the two, will pay American
$650 million.
   The two airlines, who currently have the only major single-owner
reservations systems, said in an announcement the new system should
stimulate competition.
   Computerized reservation systems are used throughout the world
for reserving airline seats, rental cars and lodging, as well as for
other travel services and management information services.
   There are currently five such systems in the United States and
six elsewhere around the world, the airlines said.
   Under the American-Delta deal, each airline will own half of the
system. Other carriers, both international and domestic, will have a
chance to buy in, but Delta and American would see their shares fall
to no less than 25 percent each.
   Max D. Hopper, American's senior vice president for information
services, will be chairman of the partnership, and the company will
be based in the Dallas-Fort Worth area, headquarters of American.
   Details of the new partnership will be filed with the U.S.
Justice Department on Monday, the airlines said.
   Reservation systems owned by single airlines have been criticized
by the federal government as giving owner-carriers an unfair
advantage over other airlines that do not have such systems.
   Delta and American said that combining their systems would
eliminate that criticism.
</TEXT>
