<FIRST>r f AM-Chrysler-Restructure     02-05 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler-Restructure,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Motors Restructures Vehicle Engineering Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Motors Corp. said Sunday it
was restructuring its vehicle engineering operations to focus
product development on an entire vehicle rather than its individual
components.
   Chrysler Motors is Chrysler Corp.'s automaking arm.
   ``This new structure will enable us to be more vehicle-oriented
instead of being component-driven,'' Francois J. Castaing, Chrysler
Motors vice president for vehicle engineering, said in a statement.
   ``We'll be looking at our vehicles as a whole entity ... from
concept to production,'' said Castaing.
   ``By reallocating our resources into smaller, dedicated groups,
we will have more concentrated responsibility and accountability,''
he said. ``It also will enable us to be more responsive to what our
customers tell us they want in a new vehicle.''
   Employment levels in the 6,000-worker Chrysler engineering
organization will be unaffected by the restructuring, the statement
said.
   Under the restructuring, the engineering operations will be
divided into four basic groups, with support units also being
created. The support units include scientific laboratories and
Chrysler's proving grounds.
</TEXT>
