<FILEID>AP-NR-02-05-89 1854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CommoditiesProbe     02-05 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Subject in FBI Probe Says Agent Looked ``Like A G-Man''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An FBI agent posing as a losing trader drew
commodities brokers into a federal investigation of their activities
by offering to help them dodge taxes on their earnings in the
futures markets, one broker said in an interview published Sunday.
   ``He made this pitch repeatedly,'' Thomas A. Crouch, a prominent
broker, told the Chicago Tribune.
   ``He'd say, `I have this big loss carryover, and I'm willing to
sell it to guys who've made a lot of money,''' Crouch said.
   Crouch was the first broker to detail in a news account how be
became a subject of the massive probe of alleged commodities fraud
at the Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   The agent, who used the alias Peter Vogel, posed as a
down-on-his-luck trader willing to use his accounts to conceal the
profits of successful traders who wanted to evade taxes, Crouch said.
   At least one trader went along with Vogel's scheme because he
felt sorry for him, said Crouch, of Ogden Dunes, Ind.
   The FBI's investigation has centered on allegations that as many
as 100 brokers and traders at Chicago's futures exchanges
systematically cheated customers out of millions of dollars in
executing their orders to buy and sell futures contracts on a
variety of commodities.
   A federal grand jury reportedly has been convened to consider the
fraud charges. More than 200 subpoenas have been served on prominent
brokers, traders and firms.
   Crouch said he traded futures contracts on Japanese yen with
Vogel, described by Crouch and others as a clean-cut, silver-haired
``hayseed.'' Vogel was introduced around the Merc as the nephew of a
South American millionaire with an interest in commodities, the
broker said.
   Sources close to the inquiry told the Tribune Vogel would suggest
to traders they secretly park their earnings in his account by
recording their trades in his name, or that they could concoct
trades with him that showed them losing money.
   Crouch said he didn't go along with it, but did seek colleagues
to participate.
   ``I heard the spiel,'' Crouch said. ``I was dumb enough to say,
`I don't want to do this, But I'll see who does'.''
   Some traders have described as particularly unsuccessful in the
futures market.
   Crouch's comments provided the first look from a trader's
perspective at the investigation that has shaken the industry since
it was disclosed last month.
   The Tribune said Crouch decided to be interviewed because he
believed he and his colleagues were betrayed by Vogel. Some were
particularly upset that Vogel used an office Christmas party in the
final weeks of the investigation to catch people off-guard and
possibly record their conversations on tape, Crouch said.
   ``To accept an invitation and then work the party is just a bit
much,'' Crouch said.
   ``This wasn't Miami Vice. This wasn't a cocaine ring,'' the
newspaper quoed Crouch as saying. ``This, at best, was a little
white-collar crime.''
   The Tribune said Vogel was one of four federal agents who posed
as traders to record thousands of potentially incriminating
conversations in restaurants, downtown apartments and the noisy pits
of the world's largest futures exchanges.
   One agent worked as Vogel's partner, another worked in the Board
of Trade's soybean pit and another traded Treasury bonds at the
Merc, the Tribune said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
