<FIRST>u f AM-Chris-Craft     02-05 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chris-Craft,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chris-Craft Goes To OMC In $58 Million Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Murray Industries Inc., maker of Chris-Craft
pleasure boats, has been sold for about $58 million to Outboard
Marine Corp., of Waukegan, Ill.
   The sale came in an unusual and spirited auction Saturday in the
courtroom of U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Alexander Paskay, who has been
overseeing Chris-Craft since Dec. 9, when it filed for protection
from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code.
   ``This company is in a terminal stage, and rigor mortis is
setting in,'' Paskay said in approving the sale, which includes all
of Murray Industries' assets except manufacturing plants in
Washington and Michigan.
   ``It's a very good development for the company,'' the judge said
of the auction price. Paskay said he did not think the company would
bring more than $20 million.
   Murray, based in Bradenton, Fla., had been virtually paralyzed
since the filing, which listed $70 million in debts and less than
$60 million in assets.
   More than 80 percent of Murray's 1,600 workers have been laid off
in the past few months, with manufacturing plants here and in North
Carolina at a virtual standstill while those in Washington, Michigan
and Indiana have already been shut down.
   Chris-Craft is the nation's oldest pleasure boat maker, making
recreational powerboats ranging from 17-foot ski boats to 50-foot
yachts. It is not connected with Chris Craft Industries Inc., the
New York-based media company.
   The company had warned it might fail without investment capital,
and had said it would be talking to potential buyers and might seek
an emergency sale to raise cash.
   By Saturday, four buyout offers were in _ the highest being $31.5
million _ and the bidding was expected to go higher at the auction.
   Chris-Craft bankruptcy attorney John Olson acted as auctioneer as
bidding opened with an offer from Outboard Marine of $40 million, a
figure reached during all-night bargaining Friday between the
company, its lenders and creditors.
   The other serious bidder was takeover specialist Irwin Jacobs,
owner of the boat builder, Genmar Industries Inc. Jacobs offered
$43.5 million.
   Genmar and Jacobs upped their offers until OMC bid $58 million
and Jacob made no further offer.
   Outside the courtroom, Jacobs was gracious in defeat. ``They're
happy, we're happy, everybody's happy,'' he said.
   OMC Boat Group President John Winn acknowledged his company paid
more than Chris-Craft is worth on paper.
   ``Based on where the company is (financially), we paid a
premium,'' Winn said. ``But five years from now we think we'll look
back and say we got a bargain.''
   New Chris-Craft boats could be under way within days of the
expected Feb. 20 closing of the sale, said Winn.
</TEXT>
