<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     02-05 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stock Prices Higher In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up in early trading against the
Japanese yen Monday while stock prices rose to a record high.
   The dollar opened at 129.75 yen, up 0.48 yen from Friday's close
of 129.27 yen.
   A dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said the dollar's higher opening
followed its rise in the Sydney market, where trading began earlier
than Tokyo. The dollar moved as high as 130.00 yen briefly during
early trading in Sydney, he said.
   ``The dollar seemed to gain further ground as nothing concrete
came out of last Friday's G-7 meeting,'' said the dealer, who spoke
anonymously.
   Finance ministers and central bank governors from the Group of
Seven industrialized countries ended their meeting in Washington
Friday. They pledged to continue close economic policy coordination
and seek ways to solve the world's huge international debt problem,
while accepting the current exchange rates.
   The G-7 is made up of the United States, Japan, Britain, France,
West Germany, Italy and Canada.
   The dealer, however, said the dollar's movement will be limited
as other financial markts in Asia, including Hong Kong and
Singapore, were closed Monday for the Chinese Lunar New Year
holiday. They will reopen Thursday.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which rose 178.48 points to a record-high close of
31,685.48 points Friday, added another 109.05 points, or 0.34
percent, in the first 15 minutes of trading to move to 31,794.83.
</TEXT>
